                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1521</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-02-26T15:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 26, 1915, 3 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 28, 9.50 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1695. Think Germany in answer, which an assembly of people from Army staff, Navy
                    staff, and Foreign Office now considering, will not only ask passage for food
                    but for raw materials such as copper, rubber, wool, cotton, and as a bid for
                    Chile’s favor, Chilean nitrates which are used for fertilizers and
                    explosives.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
